summary: Gill has signaled support for an 'America First' approach to trade and for 'fixing our uneven trade relationship with the rest of the world,' indicating a preference for renegotiation or protectionist measures to benefit U.S. interests. He promoted these themes while praising President Trump in a March 2025 press release about the Golden Age Act. He also introduced the Land and National Defense (LAND) Act to impose reciprocal restrictions on foreign purchases of U.S. agricultural land, arguing that reciprocity and limits on adversarial-country ownership of farmland are necessary to put Americans on an even footing abroad and to protect U.S. economic and food-security interests.

Opposes the executive's use of national emergency authority to impose tariffs and has pledged to support congressional efforts to terminate such tariff actions. Upon being sworn in she indicated she would sign discharge petitions to terminate President Trump's emergency tariffs on Canada and Mexico and other emergency tariff actions ("Liberation Day" tariffs), reflecting opposition to unilateral tariff actions taken without ordinary congressional process.

Favors onshoring and policies that make it easier to build in America and harder to build overseas; has publicly promoted measures to encourage American businesses to hire domestic workers and criticized practices that shift production abroad. At recent events he echoed Administration messaging that the tax code and deregulation should reward American workers and manufacturers and make it harder to employ foreigners who displace U.S. jobs, signaling a protectionist, 'buy/produce American' orientation.
